TY  - JOUR
AU  - Gurun, Umit G
AU  - Stoffman, Noah
AU  - Yonker, Scott E
T1  - Trust Busting: The Effect of Fraud on Investor Behavior
PY  - 2018
Y1  - 2018/04/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhx058
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 31
IS  - 4
SP  - 1341
EP  - 1376
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - We study the importance of trust in the investment advisory industry by exploiting the geographic dispersion of victims of the Madoff Ponzi scheme. Residents of communities that were exposed to the fraud subsequently withdrew assets from investment advisers and increased deposits at banks. Additionally, exposed advisers were more likely to close. Advisers who provided services that can build trust, such as financial planning advice, experienced fewer withdrawals. Our evidence suggests that the trust shock was transmitted through social networks. Taken together, our results show that trust plays a critical role in the financial intermediation industry.Received April 18, 2016; editorial decision March 8, 2017 by Editor Robin Greenwood.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhx058
ER  - 



